title: Determination of Neutron Scattering Cross Sections of 9-Be at Energies between 7.10 MeV and 9.97 MeV.

x4freetext: of 9-Be at Energies between 7.10 MeV and 9.97 MeV.
width 1 nanosec, and multi-angle neutron time-of-
Deuterium gas target, 1.0 cm in diameter and
3.0 cm in length, gas pressure 1.9-2.0 hPa.
.Mean neutron energy is defined within +/- 20 keV.
n/gamma discrimination with pulse shape analysis.
Five NE213 neutron detectors D1-D5 located
behind a massive collimator shielding in a distance
of 1200 cm from the sample. The angle separation
between the detectors is 12.5 deg. Detector diameter
.The angle region covered is 12.5 deg to 160 deg.
An additional NE213 detector was used as relative
fluence monitor, diameter 3.81 cm, length 3.81 cm.
The movable monitor (in a fixed distance of 651 cm)
was always in a position of 58.9 deg relative
diameter 25.1 mm, height 50.0 mm, mass 45.48 g,
placed 17.5 cm from the gas target centre.

.For the complete neutron angular distribution by
means of Monte Carlo simulated TOF spectra which was
iteratively adjusted to the measured TOF spectra.
The simulation comprised the neutron production in
the gas target and the scattering geometry between
.For parasitic neutrons from the D(d,np) breakup
reaction which were simulated and subtracted.
Error of the central point of neutron energy

An additional uncertainty of 5% of the ratio
N-bu/N-in is taken into account for the DDX
neutrons, N-in = fraction of inelastically scattered
All cross sections were extracted based on
the assumption of an isotopic abundance of Be-9
.DDX cross sections are determined in fixed emission
energy intervals. Due to the kinematics, there is a
cutoff angle for larger neutron emission energies.
Above this cutoff angle, no neutron emission is
complete angular distributions have to be available.
Therefore, dummy cross sections being very small
(below 1 mb/[sr*MeV]) were applied in these angle
regions above the cutoff angle. Angle-integrated
DDX are corrected for these dummy values. A correct
separation of the DDX cross sections stemming from
the (n,2n) reaction channels and the partial cross
section exciting the 2.43 MeV level is impossible.
In this work, the separation was tried assuming
a linear shape of the DDX continuum beneath the
inelastic 2.43 MeV peak in the TOF spectra.
